   <m>{\large \textbf{25.1 A Constrained Optimization Problem}}</m>
   <p>Goal: locate the extreme values of</p>
   <me>Q(\vec{x}) = \vec{x}^T A\vec{x}, \textup{ } \vec{x} \in \mathbb{R}^n, \textup{ } A \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times n},</me>
   <p>subject to</p>
   <me>||\vec{x}|| = 1</me>
   <p>We'd also like to determine the values of <m>Q</m> at these points.</p>
   <p><m>{\mathbf{Theorem}}</m>:</p>
   <p>If <m>Q = \vec{x}^T A\vec{x}</m>, <m>A</m> is a real <m>n \times n</m> symmetric matrix, with eigenvalues</p>
   <me>\lambda_1 \ge \lambda_2 \cdots \ge \lambda_n</me>
   <p>and associated normalized eigenvectors</p>
   <me>\vec{u}_1, \vec{u}_2, \cdots, \vec{u}_n</me>
   <p>Then, subject to the constraint <m>||\vec{x}|| = 1</m>,</p>
   <ul>
    <li>
        <p>
            the <m>\textbf{maximum}</m> value of <m>Q(\vec{x}) = \lambda_1</m>, attained at <m>\vec{x} = \pm \vec{u}_1</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            the <m>\textbf{minimum}</m> value of <m>Q(\vec{x}) = \lambda_n</m>, attained at <m>\vec{x} = \pm \vec{u}_n</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
   </ul>
   <m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p>
   <p><m>{\textbf{25.1.1 Example}}</m>:</p>
   <p>Calculate the maximum and minimum values of the quadratic form <m>Q</m> subject to the constraint <m>||\vec{x}|| = 1</m>. Identify where this maximum is obtained.</p>
   <me>Q(\vec{x}) = 4{x_1}^2 + {x_2}^2 + 4x_1 x_2 + 3{x_3}^2, \textup{ } \vec{x} \in \mathbb{R}^3</me>
    </page>
    <page>
        <m>{\large \textbf{25.2 Orthogonality Constraints}}</m>
        <p><m>{\mathbf{Theorem}}</m>:</p>
        <p>Suppose <m>Q = \vec{x}^T A\vec{x}</m>, where <m>A \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times n}</m> is symmetric and has eigenvalues</p>
        <me>\lambda_1 \ge \lambda_2 \cdots \ge \lambda_n</me>
        <p>and associated eigenvectors</p>
        <me>\vec{u}_1, \vec{u}_2, \cdots, \vec{u}_n</me>
        <p>Subject to the constraints <m>||\vec{x}|| = 1</m> and <m>\vec{x} \cdot \vec{u}_1 = 0</m>,</p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    the maximum value of <m>Q(\vec{x}) = \lambda_2</m>, attained at <m>\vec{x} = \vec{u}_2</m>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    the minimum value of <m>Q(\vec{x}) = \lambda_n</m>, attained at <m>\vec{x} = \vec{u}_n</m>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
        <m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p>
        <p><m>{\textbf{25.2.1 Example}}</m>:</p>
        <p>Calculate the maximum and minimum values of <m>Q</m> subject to <m>||\vec{x}|| = 1</m> and <m>\vec{x} \cdot \vec{u} = 0</m>.</p>
        <me>Q(\vec{x}) = 4{x_1}^2 + {x_2}^2 + 4x_1 x_2 + 3{x_3}^2, \textup{ } \vec{u} = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}</me>
    </page>
